'''Patrick Bingham-Hall''' is an [[Architectural photographers|architectural photographer]] who came to prominence in the 1990s.<ref>Architectural Review Australia, Summer 1998, page 38. 'Literal not metaphorical', by Kate Stewart.</ref> &nbsp;He is also an [[Architecture|architectural]] writer and editor, and owns Pesaro Publishing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pesaropublishing.com |title=Pesaro Publishing |publisher=Pesaro Publishing |date=2010-07-28 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> which publishes books on architecture and [[design]].

==Education==
He was born on 15 July 1958 in Aden in [[Yemen]], where his father (Group Captain T. L. Bingham-Hall) was in command of the [[Royal Air Force]] base, and spent his early years in [[London]] before emigrating to [[Australia]] in 1963.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}  He was educated at [[Sydney Church of England Grammar School]] (Shore) and studied [[philosophy]] at [[Macquarie University]] for one year, before taking up [[photography]] at [[Sydney College of the Arts]].  He left in his second year to start his own photographic studio, and specialized in [[rock and roll]] photography, working with bands like [[Radio Birdman]] and [[The Saints (band)|The Saints]].  His cover photograph of the Radio Birdman album ''Living Eyes''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.msn.com/music/album/radio-birdman/living-eyes-more-fun |title=Living Eyes/More Fun by Radio Birdman on MSN Music |publisher=Music.msn.com |date=2005-04-26 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> became an iconic image of the [[Underground music|underground rock]] scene in Australia.

==Career==

He switched to architectural photography in the early 1980s, and traveled the world to study architectural history and to photograph classic buildings.  Many of these photographs were included in his first (self-published) book ''Monumental Irony''.<ref>RAIA NSW Architecture Bulletin, August 1986. 'Monumental Irony', book review by Frank Stanisic</ref>  In the 1990s he took the photographs for many books on Australian architecture, and was selected as editor of the book that documented the architecture for the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Olympic Games]].<ref>The Australian, January 17, 2000, p.&nbsp;18. 'Making History', book review by Peter Ward</ref>  He also wrote ''Austral Eden'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecturemedia.com/aa/aaissue.php?issueid=199909&article=5&typeon=1 |title=AA - Books - September/October 1999 |publisher=Architecturemedia.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> an idiosyncratic history of Australian architecture, and contributed articles to magazines in Australia and [[England]].<ref>Building Design magazine, September 10, 1999</ref>  In 1999, he formed his own publishing company,<ref>The Australian Financial Review, November 6, 1999, p.&nbsp:14. 'Drawing rooms to sit the way Australians live', by Anne Susskind</ref> Pesaro Publishing, which was to publish many books on Australian architecture within a few years.  Bingham-Hall was usually editor and photographer.  Most of his early books for Pesaro were done in collaboration with [[Philip Goad]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ruralshed.com.au/rural-shed-articles/2001/11/3/beyond-the-tin-shed |title=Beyond The Tin Shed |publisher=Ruralshed.com.au |date=2001-11-03 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> an architectural writer and [[academic]] from [[Melbourne]].  After publishing ''Architecture Bali''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.architecturemedia.com/aa/aaissue.php?issueid=200101&article=8&typeon=1 |title=AA - Books - January/February 2001 |publisher=Architecturemedia.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> in 2000, Bingham-Hall decided to expand his publishing into [[Asia]], while continuing to produce books on Australian architecture.<ref>Sydney Morning Herald (Domain), April 21, 2005, p.&nbsp;12. 'He's in the Good Books', by Julia Richardson</ref>  He also writes many of the books himself, particularly on tropical architecture in Asia.  He is the author of monographs on [[WOHA]] Architects, Guz Architects, [[Peter Stutchbury]], and CKOA, and a book on houses in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region.


Patrick Bingham-Hall is married to Katrina, and they have five children - Salty Netty Bingham-Hall, Pepe Jay Bingham-Hall, Rosemary Alice Bingham-Hall, Thomas James Bingham-Hall and William Ginger Bingham-Hall.  His house in [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain, Sydney]], was designed by [[Rex Addison]],<ref>{{cite web |title=BINGHAM-HALL HOUSE|author=MICHAEL TAWA|publisher=Architecture Media Pty Ltd|work=Architecture Australia|url=http://www.architecturemedia.com/aa/aaissue.php?issueid=200305&article=7&typeon=2}}</ref> although he has now lived in [[Singapore]] for many years.

